<subSubSection id="C7FA60B2FFE460296AE7CC5DC9F8AE22" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="17" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8F5F3339FFE460366AE7CC5DCD3CADDA" blockId="15.[151,1436,1904,2010]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
Diagnosis. 
<taxonomicName id="48E048BAFFE460366B6CCC5DCA26AD89" authorityName="Cartwright" authorityYear="2008" baseAuthorityName="Cartwright" baseAuthorityYear="2008" box="[284,514,1904,1929]" class="Insecta" family="Ecnomidae" genus="Daternomina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trulla">
<emphasis id="BD94EF2BFFE460366B6CCC5DCA26AD89" box="[284,514,1904,1929]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Daternomina trulla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName id="48E048BAFFE4603668F9CC5DCACBAD89" authorityName="Cartwright" authorityYear="2008" box="[649,751,1904,1929]" class="Insecta" family="Ecnomidae" genus="Daternomina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ulltra">
<emphasis id="BD94EF2BFFE4603668F9CC5DCACBAD89" box="[649,751,1904,1929]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">D. ulltra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in possessing rounded apices on the superior appendages and inferior appendages which are short, fused basally and curved laterally, but differs in having a relatively shallow notch distally, dividing at most the distal quarter and a weakly down curved phallic guide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8F5F3339FFFB60296AB6CBB5CC16ABA2" blockId="16.[151,1436,152,1058]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Description. (Revised after 
<bibRefCitation id="EB714EC8FFFB60296864CBB5CA98AAB2" author="Neboiss, A." box="[532,700,152,178]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="271 - 325" refId="ref52169" refString="Neboiss, A. (1982) The caddis-flies (Trichoptera) of south-western Australia. Australian Journal of Zoology, 30, 271 - 325." type="journal article" year="1982">Neboiss 1982</bibRefCitation>
). Head, body and wings brown; wings similar to 
<taxonomicName id="48E048BAFFFB60296F68CBB5CDB8AAB1" authorityName="Kimmins" authorityYear="1953" box="[1304,1436,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Ecnomidae" genus="Ecnomina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="irrorata">
<emphasis id="BD94EF2BFFFB60296F68CBB5CDB8AAB1" box="[1304,1436,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">D. irrorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="17DB2FBCFFFB60296AEFCBEDC8C3AADA" box="[159,231,192,218]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1442,1466]" captionTargetBox="[300,1279,186,1428]" captionTargetId="figure-123@7.[291,1287,160,1428]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. 1–2. Daternomina irrorata (Kimmins). 1: Forewing and hindwing. 2: Head and thorax, dorsal view. 3– 6. Ecnomina spp. 3. Ecnomina legula Neboiss, forewing and hindwing. 4–5. Ecnomina scutica sp. nov. 4: Head and thorax, dorsal view. 5: Wings, section of forewing and hindwing. 6. Ecnomina spinosa Kimmins, head and thorax, dorsal view. n., nygma; o.w, occipital wart." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5124137" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5124137/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Forewing length about 3 times width: male 4.0– 
<quantity id="48189EDCFFFB6029693CCBEDCB88AADA" box="[844,940,192,218]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.4" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="4.4">4.4 mm</quantity>
. Forewing fork 2 relatively long, sessile, length about 1.7–2.0 times length of fork 3, nygma present; fork 3 relatively long, length about 1.8–2.7 times length footstalk, footstalk length about 1.4–2.3 times length cross-vein m; r-m and m displaced at fork 3 by about 1.7–1.8 times length cross-vein m; fork 4 length similar to fork 3; fork 5 long, length about 1.8 times length of fork 4. Hindwing length about 3 times width; fork 2 with short footstalk, length footstalk 0.9–1.2 times length cross-vein r-m, fork 2 length about 1.4–1.7 times length of fork 3.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8F5F3339FFFB60296AB6CA9DC940A8BA" blockId="16.[151,1436,152,1058]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Male. Tergum X membranous (
<figureCitation id="17DB2FBCFFFB60296838CA9DCA80ABCA" box="[584,676,432,458]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–24" captionStartId="15.[151,269,1367,1391]" captionTargetBox="[317,1269,218,1325]" captionTargetId="figure-130@15.[308,1275,208,1339]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 19–24. Daternomina spp. Male genitalia in lateral, ventral and dorsal views. 19–21: Daternomina ulltra sp. nov. 22–24: Daternomina trulla (Neboiss)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5124145" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5124145/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
). Superior appendages slightly laterally compressed; in lateral view, broad, length about 2.5 times width (
<figureCitation id="17DB2FBCFFFB602968EDCAF5CADCABF2" box="[669,760,472,498]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–24" captionStartId="15.[151,269,1367,1391]" captionTargetBox="[317,1269,218,1325]" captionTargetId="figure-130@15.[308,1275,208,1339]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 19–24. Daternomina spp. Male genitalia in lateral, ventral and dorsal views. 19–21: Daternomina ulltra sp. nov. 22–24: Daternomina trulla (Neboiss)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5124145" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5124145/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
); in dorsal view, length about 3.5 times width, with two groups of spines on inner surface (
<figureCitation id="17DB2FBCFFFB6029685FC92DCAA3A81A" box="[559,647,512,538]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–24" captionStartId="15.[151,269,1367,1391]" captionTargetBox="[317,1269,218,1325]" captionTargetId="figure-130@15.[308,1275,208,1339]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 19–24. Daternomina spp. Male genitalia in lateral, ventral and dorsal views. 19–21: Daternomina ulltra sp. nov. 22–24: Daternomina trulla (Neboiss)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5124145" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5124145/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
). Phallus generally tube-like with a pair of elongate processes dorsally; with a single relatively long and slender, curved process (phallic guide) arising from near the base of the inferior appendages (
<figureCitation id="17DB2FBCFFFB60296BEAC97DC9DDA86A" box="[410,505,592,618]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–24" captionStartId="15.[151,269,1367,1391]" captionTargetBox="[317,1269,218,1325]" captionTargetId="figure-130@15.[308,1275,208,1339]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 19–24. Daternomina spp. Male genitalia in lateral, ventral and dorsal views. 19–21: Daternomina ulltra sp. nov. 22–24: Daternomina trulla (Neboiss)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5124145" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5124145/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
). Inferior appendages strongly dorso-ventrally compressed; in ventral view, fused, robust, rounded sided, with a short, narrow V-shaped notch distally (
<figureCitation id="17DB2FBCFFFB60296E7AC955CC46A892" box="[1034,1122,632,658]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–24" captionStartId="15.[151,269,1367,1391]" captionTargetBox="[317,1269,218,1325]" captionTargetId="figure-130@15.[308,1275,208,1339]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 19–24. Daternomina spp. Male genitalia in lateral, ventral and dorsal views. 19–21: Daternomina ulltra sp. nov. 22–24: Daternomina trulla (Neboiss)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5124145" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5124145/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
); in lateral view, relatively straight (
<figureCitation id="17DB2FBCFFFB60296A8FC98DC972A8BA" box="[255,342,672,698]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–24" captionStartId="15.[151,269,1367,1391]" captionTargetBox="[317,1269,218,1325]" captionTargetId="figure-130@15.[308,1275,208,1339]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 19–24. Daternomina spp. Male genitalia in lateral, ventral and dorsal views. 19–21: Daternomina ulltra sp. nov. 22–24: Daternomina trulla (Neboiss)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5124145" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5124145/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
